FeedPackage.Description: The EventStore is a persistence library used to abstract different storage implementations when using event sourcing as storage mechanism. Event sourcing is most closely associated with a concept known as CQRS. The purpose of the EventStore is to represent a series of events as a stream. Furthermore, it provides hooks whereby any events committed to the stream can be dispatched to interested parties. The EventStore liberates application developers from this level of infrastructure awareness and concern by committing all work within a separate isolated atomic unit--all without using transactions. Furthermore, it does this outside of any ambient transaction from a message queue or other persistence mechanisms.
FeedPackage.Summary: EventStore for CQRS projects. The EventStore is a persistence library used to abstract different storage implementations when using event sourcing as storage mechanism.

FeedPackage.Authors: Event Store LLP, all contributors to the repository
FeedPackage.Description: A client library for EventStore
FeedPackage.ReleaseNotes:
Release Notes:

FeedPackage.Description:
On top of EventStore, the JSON Serializer is a plugin serializer for saving events to a commit stream.
The EventStore is a persistence library used to abstract different storage implementations when using event sourcing as storage mechanism. Event sourcing is most closely associated with a concept known as CQRS. The purpose of the EventStore is to represent a series of events as a stream. Furthermore, it provides hooks whereby any events committed to the stream can be dispatched to interested parties. The EventStore liberates application developers from this level of infrastructure awareness and concern by committing all work within a separate isolated atomic unit--all without using transactions. Furthermore, it does this outside of any ambient transaction from a message queue or other persistence mechanisms.
FeedPackage.Summary: EventStore for CQRS projects. The EventStore is a persistence library used to abstract different storage implementations when using event sourcing as storage mechanism.

v2.8.9 BUG FIX: Linq exception when deserializing some generic types.
v2.8.8 BUG FIX: Cannot (de)serialize IEnumerable<T> when defined in abstraction map
v2.8.7 BUG FIX: GUID serialization should be automatically registered. BUG FIX: Removing types from the type registry causes null reference exception. Added JetBrains.Annotations attributes.
v2.8.6 Made schema validation errors more precise.
v2.8.5 BUG FIX: Validation of schemas using JsonSchema.Draft04 not working properly.
v2.8.4 BUG FIX: Enum deserialization does not respect CaseSensitiveDeserialization option
v2.8.3 BUG FIX: Draft04 not self-validating. Affected enum schemas as well.
v2.8.2.1 (no functional changes) Removed JetBrains.Annotations from project (could interfere with their Nuget package). Added reference to the Nuget package published by JetBrains.
v2.8.2 Added enum serialization format autodetection to deserialization. BUG FIX: Schema basic type definitions serialize as full schema. BUG FIX: #Def key is not added when only two references are present.
v2.8.1 Updated default resolver to look at non-public constructors as well as public. Added exception when default constructor cannot instantiate a type.
v2.8.0.2 Rebuilt libraries and repackaged. No functional changes from v2.8.0.1.
v2.8.0.1 BUG FIX: Nullables with default values may be ignored.
v2.8.0 (may contain breaking changes) Added auto-registration of specific generic types. Removed specific generic type registration methods from JsonSerializationTypeRegistry. Replaced usages of JsonValueParseException and JsonKeyParseException with JsonSyntaxException. Removed JsonValueParseException and JsonKeyParseException.

Bug fix: Member.ClearNitifications() throws "cannot POST..." Bug fix: TrelloService.Me always returns null Reduced net traffic by specifying which entity fields to download Updated incomplete Actions & Notifications with Debug method that throws an exception as notification during development Member.Preferences updated to conform to changes by Trello Dev Team Added MarkForUpdate() method on all entities Changed Board.IsPinned to read-only to conform with Trello API Completed functional tests, fixing a lot of other bugs.

Updated TrelloService to throw exceptions rather than catching them and exposing them through a property. Updated CheckList.AddCheckItem() to use CheckItemStateType rather than bool in the parameter list. Changed Organization.AddBoard() to CreateBoard() to match the call on Member. Added Member.ClosedBoards property. Added option to specify model types to return on TrelloService.Search(). Added option to specify a search context on TrelloService.Search(). Updated extension methods to use any available API calls rather than just using LINQ.

FeedPackage.Description:
My packageExample of owin middleware that "fixes" Unity's PerRequestLifetimeManager failure to dispose objects.
When using Unity as your dependency injection container in an Owin site you cannot use the UnityPerRequestHttpModule, which is responsible for diposing of objects registered with PerRequestLifetimeManager. Simply removing it causes these resources to leak, until cleaned up by the garbage collector.
This middleware manages the cleanup tasks previously done by UnityPerRequestHttpModule. The line "DynamicModuleUtility.RegisterModule(typeof(UnityPerRequestHttpModule));" is no longer required.
FeedPackage.Title: RequestLifetimeMiddleware

FeedPackage.Description:
THIS IS BROKEN AND UNSUPPORTED, DO NOT USE THIS
My packageExample of owin middleware that "fixes" Unity's PerRequestLifetimeManager failure to dispose objects.
When using Unity as your dependency injection container in an Owin site you cannot use the UnityPerRequestHttpModule, which is responsible for diposing of objects registered with PerRequestLifetimeManager. Simply removing it causes these resources to leak, until cleaned up by the garbage collector.
This middleware manages the cleanup tasks previously done by UnityPerRequestHttpModule. The line "DynamicModuleUtility.RegisterModule(typeof(UnityPerRequestHttpModule));" is no longer required.
FeedPackage.ReleaseNotes: Interface breaking change to extension method name to be more consistant. Also, Changed key for registering middleware.
FeedPackage.Title: RequestLifetimeMiddleware

FeedPackage.Description: RequestReduce allows any IIS based website to automaticaly sprite background images into a single optimized PNG as well as combine and minify CSS and Javascript with absolutely no coding beyond a few config tweaks. RequestReduce excercises common best practices when serving its javascript, css and sprited images ensuring that the appropriate caching headers are sent to the browser so that browsers will not need to pull down a new http response until absolutely necessary. Chances are you will see an immediate rise in your yslow and google page speed tests.
FeedPackage.Summary: RequestReduce is a .Net Library and HttpModule providing automatic CSS background image optimization and spriting as well as CSS and Javascript merging and minification.
FeedPackage.Tags: CSS Minification Sprites Website Performance Optimization Compression Minify Javascript
FeedPackage.Title: RequestReduce
